post_text:
Wildorado Rodeo Club
Tri State Finals
Canadian, Texas

...I've earned scars and I've earned buckles
Been in the chutes with blood on my knuckles
I've driven all night long, tryin' to make a rodeo
I'm strong as a freight train, just as steady
Crack the gate, you know I'll be ready
And I'm gonna hang on until the ride is through
'Cause that's what cowboys (and cowgirls) do...

We are PROUD of each of these Mustangs - it’s awesome seeing them excel in rodeo along with all the other things they do so well! They really are “strong as a freight train” and always “ready” when called on! Keep it up and best of luck!

post_text: Hello parents. We wanted to provide a reminder about return of school materials and equipment. Monday, May 18 and Tuesday, May 19 the Wildorado ISD buses will be at the meal drop sites from 7:30-8:30 am. We ask that you return your child’s materials (a list of materials to return will be sent to you via staff) one if these two mornings. The buses will be at Wildorado old Elementary School, Hereford Tractor Supply, and Home Depot Amarillo Soncy/I-40. Staff will be available at Wildorado school from 8:00-4:00 on Wednesday, May 20 to gather any student belongings left in athletic lockers. These materials will be bagged and delivered to cars in the school parking lot.

May 1st, 2020
National School Principals’ Day:

Please take the time to thank our educational leader, Mrs. Sherry Clark, for all she does for our school. Throughout the school year with many ups and downs, she has kept a focused commitment to lead our young people. She works hard to support and guide our teachers and staff. She guides our academic success and sets the tone for our school. Beyond this, she loves the students of Wildorado ISD and pushes to see them become successful in all their endeavors.

The National Weather Service is predicting a winter storm beginning this Monday evening through Wednesday. They are currently expecting between 4-7 inches of snow.

***As a result of this possibility of inclement weather, the boys and girls varsity basketball games against Adrian and the homecoming events previously scheduled for this coming Tuesday, have all been moved to this Monday, February 10th. The varsity girls will play at 5:00 and the varsity boys will play at 6:30***

***The JV girls game against Caprock is still scheduled for tomorrow at 4:00 as originally planned***

***This week’s junior high games have been moved to Thursday, February 13th, at 5:00 and 6:00 pm***

Come out and support the Mustangs and Lady Mustangs!! Go Big Blue!!

During severe weather season and with the possibility of severe weather today (ex. currently under moderate effect for parts of the Texas Panhandle - KFDA), we would like everyone in the area to know that the underground storm shelter at the "old school", across from the post office, is open and available to anyone who wishes to utilize it @ 307 N. Locust, Wildorado, TX. Also, WISD students and staff have access to a storm shelter during the school day.
-WISD

post_text:
Happy Flag Day!
.........
You're a grand old flag,
You're a high flying flag
And forever in peace may you wave.
You're the emblem of
The land I love.
The home of the free and the brave.
Ev'ry heart beats true
'neath the Red, White and Blue,
Where there's never a boast or brag.
Should auld acquaintance be forgot,
Keep your eye on the grand old flag.

post_text: We use the term transference in education which simply means moving what we learned in the classroom into practice outside the classroom. Our kindergarteners are experiencing that today as they go from learning about plant life in the classroom to actually experiencing it with some hands on learning out near the playground...not to mention the fact that they are helping with our beautification program by pulling some weeds along the way 😀! Good job (again) Kindergarten!

post_text:
Thank you Sedrick Knowlton, WTAMU Assistant Director, for coming to Wildorado today to present to our 8th & 9th grade students and thank you Mrs. Duck, our counselor, for setting it up! Mr. Knowlton did a great job of presenting on the topics of college admissions, scholarships, early involvement/connectedness on campus, and focusing early on academics - starting now! He also made it all interesting and relevant. Be sure to ask your student about “buffalo, tree, ground!” 😀 Good job students - you did great too! Go Big Blue!

Amarillo College will be here May 4th for another important meeting with our students.

Today our 3rd grade scientists used the "big kid" science lab to perform a water cycle experiment. We are not sure how we can create the right environment to make it rain here in the Texas Panhandle, but as the 2nd grade observed, we were able to form clouds and make rain in our experiment.
- Mrs. Welch, 2nd/3rd grade science

These Mustangs are the Real Deal!

This past weekend they competed in rodeo events and stood out in numerous areas! They have now qualified to compete in Gonzales, TX near the end of May. They will be competing against other top competitors from all the Regions of Texas....now that’s saying something!!

Left to Right -

Wesley Martin: team roping and breakaway roping.

Stockton Blount: calf roping, shoot dogging, goat tying, and team roping.

Hance Albracht: shoot dogging, team roping, calf roping, and goat tying.

Brooke Madill: pole bending, ribbon roping, and breakaway roping.

AWESOME JOB! We are PROUD of you.

post_text: Tonight’s Christmas Program was AWESOME! The students were REAL SUPERSTARS. GREAT JOB! Thanks to everyone who helped put this production together. We ESPECIALLY want to THANK the DYNAMIC director/producer - the ALWAYS AWESOME - Mrs. Michelle Gruhlkey!! You’ve been a BLESSING to our school AGAIN - thank you for pouring yourself into our students/school! We wish you ALL a VERY MERRY CHRISTMAS!!

post_text:
The Mustangs were in action tonight as our junior high boys and girls teams took on Boys Ranch. The girls fought hard and after a back and forth and back and forth game came up just a few points shy while the junior high boys applied lots of defensive pressure and demonstrated an impressive offensive in their lopsided win! We are proud of all our Mustang athletes - Coach Austin Johnson and Coach Kyle Johnson have them hustling for every loose ball, playing tenacious defense, and aggressively attacking the basket on offense. These Mustangs are tough and only getting better and better.
It’s going to be a fun season - Go Big Blue!

post_text:
Football picture sharing of the last game of this season:

Great job Mustangs!
•"The main ingredient of stardom is the rest of the team" - not yourself.
•"Success comes from knowing that you did your best to become the best that you are capable of becoming."
•"Success is never final; failure is never fatal. It's courage that counts."
Here's to becoming a TEAM this season! Here's to doing your best! Here's to the fact that you celebrated your wins and accomplishments TOGETHER and you rallied and encouraged each other when things didn't go the way you had hoped. Especially, here's to you for being COURAGEOUS and facing each challenge together by looking them right in the eye, arm in arm and not blinking but instead taking each one head on as a team! Great job Mustangs! Great job coaches! [Blaze Herring, Cody Bonds, Kyle Johnson]. You started a tradition and set the bar high for all who shall follow. We are PROUD OF YOU!
*Now let's lace up those high tops & meet them at center count! 🏀
GO BIG BLUE!

post_text: Today our 4th grade students trained under Gary Hogg, a fascinating and skilled author! He isn't only an expressive, funny, and extremely interesting writer but he's also an exceptional teacher. Today he taught our 4th graders about "putting your brain with your heart so you'll come out twice as smart". This refers to adding specific details, therefore interest, into the writing. He went on to discuss personal narratives and emphasized the "one, two punch" meaning ONE main event with lots of details and the TWO meaning we should think TWICE about what we want to say before putting it down on paper. The students gave lots of great feedback and input. They will surely come out more creative and detail focused writers after today's writing workshop. Great job Mustangs & thanks again to Gary Hogg for this wonderful experience!

post_text:
Picture sharing:
3rd grade teaching the preschool students what they learned about butterflies on the field trip to the Amarillo Botanical Gardens: how cool is this?! Not that you needed extra proof beyond the obvious of how great this is but an educational researcher, Edgar Dale, did a study and produced the "Cone of Knowledge" or "Cone of Learning" which states that students remember 10% of what they read, 20% of what they hear, 30% of what they see, 50% of what they hear and see, 70% of what they discuss with others, 80% of what they personally experience and 95% of what they teach others. That's a long explanation to just say that the field trip was turned into a great learning experience for your Mustangs! 😀 It's what they call teaching with intentionality and it's what the teachers at WISD do on a daily basis. Way to go students - way to go staff! We are proud of you!

post_text: Today was a beautiful day for some outside learning and that's exactly what our 2nd and 3rd grade did on today's field trip to the Amarillo Botanical Garden. These students, with the help of Mrs. Welch and Mrs. Tarver, know that learning does NOT have to happen in the classroom only! They compared moths and butterflies, made a craft that showed the lifecycle of butterflies, toured the beautiful gardens and of course had lunch and played at the park. Fresh air & fresh ideas! Way to go 2nd & 3rd grade!

Our students did a great job of participating and representing our school and community! Thank you FFA Travel Team, great job students, and a special thank you to Wendy and Shane Jackson for hosting these officers in their home last night so that they could present this morning.
Go Big Blue!

post_text: Thank you to everyone who made tonight's Meet & Greet - Hamburger Cookout such a huge success! We had a BLAST! It was really good seeing the students, parents, families, staff, and board members all sitting together and socializing over the wonderful meal. It was cooked by our excellent school board members and served by our phenomenal PTO! Thanks for attending - it was a great way to kickoff the new school year and we know we'll have many, many more opportunities to join together for fun, fellowship and to celebrate these most amazing students! We wish everyone a wonderful and restful weekend. We can't wait to see the students back on Monday!

We are celebrating the PHENOMENAL Mrs. Sandi Luster for Administrative Professionals Day (actually it was yesterday...shhhhh....don't tell her)!

Sandi,

We are really thankful for you. We hope you know how much we love and appreciate you! You do SO MUCH for our school, students, and staff. You are definitely a TRUE BLUE MUSTANG and our own Office Ninja!

Everyone else,

This is a great time to let Sandi know how much you appreciate her too! She tends to sick students, (sometimes even sick teachers 😀), oversees the cafeteria, student data, phone calls and getting kids on the correct bus, more emails & paperwork than any of us knows, etc. etc. etc. and does so with dedicated devotion and a smile (usually - hee-hee!).
Be sure to let her know what she means to you!!

Thanks Sandi - you're the best!

Mike Jackson,

Wildorado ISD wants to let you know how much we appreciate you for your recent volunteer work at our new school. We are extremely grateful to you for your hard work regarding the planting of over 6 acres of grass seed around our campus! This was a gift that will keep on giving and our students and community will reap the long term benefits of your dedication to our community, school and students. This was a huge gift for which we are so thankful!! Thank you, thank you, thank you. You are a True Blue Mustang!

- The Wildorado ISD staff, administration, board, students, and community.

post_text: One great day!
text: One great day!

post_text:
I hope everyone had as great a day as I did today! I started with spending time in the kindergarten room (Mrs. Martin's) and had the ABSOLUTE BEST READERS read me some amazing stories! Not much later I was treated to some gravity defying gymnastics in Ms. Palmer's 3rd grade Phys. Ed. class (I even did a cartwheel myself - seriously!). This was followed up by my observing the 7th graders constructing some jaw dropping chalk art for Mrs. Johnson. I'm sure you're asking yourself how could you top all that...? Well, I did! I ended my day by being in a skit with the best teachers in the country and performed in front of the best of the best students in the world...along with some of our finest community members at today's STAAR Pep Rally! Now that's one TERRIFIC day!!
-Mr. Duck, the blessed

post_text:
🏀🏀🏀Yep, that's sure enough what they did tonight - Win Big! They just did it, then did it again! The girls and boys teams both picked up big wins and cruised to easy victories by out hustling, out working and out scoring their opponents as they've done all season long. This completes the perfect basketball season for the girls as they remain UNDEFEATED!! The boys have throttled teams all season long too and only dropped one or two games against teams of older players as they've had to play up all season. Both teams had INCREDIBLE seasons and made lots and lots of memories. We are all so very proud of each and every one of our athletes! GREAT JOB MUSTANGS AND LADY MUSTANGS!!🏀🏀🏀

🏀🏀🏀Also, we would not have had the super successful season we had without the two BEST coaches ever! Thank you and congrats on another great season COACH AUSTIN JOHNSON & COACH PALMER!🏀🏀🏀

Go Big Blue! Go!
